&gt; &gt;  My specific class relies on its parent to execute most of the hard work
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  public class DB1Validation extends DBValidation {
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  public String ds = &quot;jdbc/DB1&quot;;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  public static final TestSuite suite()
&gt;
&gt; &gt;       {
&gt;
&gt; &gt;           TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(DB1Valida tion.class) ;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;           String[] tables = new String[]
&gt;
&gt; &gt;                   {&quot;ERRORS&quot;, &quot;ERROR_CODES&quot; , &quot;EVENTS&quot;, &quot;MASKS&quot; };
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  suite.addTest( validateAllTable s(tables) );
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  return suite;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;       }
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  }
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  If I don&#39;t create a suite-method, the code DB1Validation invokes the
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  parent test (accessDBSuccessful l) successfully. If I do create a suite
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  method as indicated, I get the following error :
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  &lt;pre&gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  junit.framework. AssertionFailedE rror: No tests found in (snipped)
&gt;
&gt; &gt;  .env.db.DB1Validati on
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; What is happening is that JUnit 4&#39;s backwards compatibility kicks in
&gt;
&gt; when it sees a suite() method in the test class. It then proceeds to
&gt;
&gt; look for test methods defined with the JUnit 3.8-style signatures
&gt;
&gt; rather than based on the JUnit 4 annotations.
